# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dynamic-range-compression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] The motivation for audio signal processing began at the beginning of the 20th century with inventions like the telephone, phonograph, and radio that allowed for the transmission and storage of audio signals.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Audio processing was necessary for early radio broadcasting, as there were many problems with studio-to-transmitter links.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] The theory of signal processing and its application to audio was largely developed at Bell Labs in the mid 20th century.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Claude Shannon and Harry Nyquist's early work on communication theory, sampling theory and pulse-code modulation (PCM) laid the foundations for the field.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] In 1957, Max Mathews became the first person to synthesize audio from a computer, giving birth to computer music.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Major developments in digital audio coding and audio data compression include differential pulse-code modulation (DPCM) by C.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Chapin Cutler at Bell Labs in 1950, linear predictive coding (LPC) by Fumitada Itakura (Nagoya University) and Shuzo Saito (Nippon Telegraph and Telephone) in 1966, adaptive DPCM (ADPCM) by P.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Flanagan at Bell Labs in 1973, discrete cosine transform (DCT) coding by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Rao in 1974, and modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) coding by J.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Bradley at the University of Surrey in 1987.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] LPC is the basis for perceptual audio coding and is widely used in speech coding, while MDCT coding is widely used in modern audio coding formats such as MP3 and Advanced Audio Coding (AAC).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] An analog audio signal is a continuous signal represented by an electrical voltage or current that is *analogous* to the sound waves in the air.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Analog signal processing then involves physically altering the continuous signal by changing the voltage or current or charge via electrical circuits.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Historically, before the advent of widespread digital technology, analog was the only method by which to manipulate a signal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Since that time, as computers and software have become more capable and affordable, digital signal processing has become the method of choice.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] However, in music applications, analog technology is often still desirable as it often produces nonlinear responses that are difficult to replicate with digital filters.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] A digital representation expresses the audio waveform as a sequence of symbols, usually binary numbers.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] This permits signal processing using digital circuits such as digital signal processors, microprocessors and general-purpose computers.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Most modern audio systems use a digital approach as the techniques of digital signal processing are much more powerful and efficient than analog domain signal processing.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Audio signal processing is used when broadcasting audio signals in order to enhance their fidelity or optimize for bandwidth or latency.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] In this domain, the most important audio processing takes place just before the transmitter.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] The audio processor here must prevent or minimize overmodulation, compensate for non-linear transmitters (a potential issue with medium wave and shortwave broadcasting), and adjust overall loudness to the desired level.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Active noise control is a technique designed to reduce unwanted sound.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] By creating a signal that is identical to the unwanted noise but with the opposite polarity, the two signals cancel out due to destructive interference.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Audio synthesis is the electronic generation of audio signals.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] A musical instrument that accomplishes this is called a synthesizer.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Synthesizers can either imitate sounds or generate new ones.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Audio synthesis is also used to generate human speech using speech synthesis.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Audio effects alter the sound of a musical instrument or other audio source.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Musicians, audio engineers and record producers use effects units during live performances or in the recording studio, typically with electric guitar, bass guitar, electronic keyboard or electric piano.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] While effects are most frequently used with electric or electronic instruments, they can be used with any audio source, such as acoustic instruments, drums, and vocals.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Computer audition (CA) or machine listening is the general field of study of algorithms and systems for audio interpretation by machines.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Since the notion of what it means for a machine to "hear" is very broad and somewhat vague, computer audition attempts to bring together several disciplines that originally dealt with specific problems or had a concrete application in mind.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Inspired by models of human audition, CA deals with questions of representation, transduction, grouping, use of musical knowledge and general sound semantics for the purpose of performing intelligent operations on audio and music signals by the computer.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/audio-signal-processing] Technically, this requires a combination of methods from the fields of signal processing, auditory modelling, music perception and cognition, pattern recognition, and machine learning, as well as more traditional methods of artificial intelligence for musical knowledge representation.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A dedicated electronic hardware unit or audio software that applies compression is called a **compressor**.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In the 2000s, compressors became available as software plugins that run in digital audio workstation software.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In recorded and live music, compression parameters may be adjusted to change the way they affect sounds.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compression and limiting are identical in process but different in degree and perceived effect.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A limiter is a compressor with a high ratio and, generally, a short attack time.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is used to improve performance and clarity in public address systems, as an effect and to improve consistency in mixing and mastering.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] It is used on voice to reduce sibilance and in broadcasting and advertising specifically to make an audio program stand out.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] It is an integral technology in some noise reduction systems.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] There are two types of compression: downward and upward.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Both types of compression reduce the dynamic range of an audio signal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Some compressors also have the ability to do the *opposite* of compression, namely *expansion*.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Expansion *increases* the dynamic range of the audio signal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Like compression, expansion comes in two types, downward and upward.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The signal entering a compressor is split; one copy is sent to a variable-gain amplifier and the other to a *side-chain* where the signal level is measured and a circuit controlled by the measured signal level applies the required gain to the amplifier.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This design, known as a *feed-forward* type, is used today in most compressors.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Earlier designs were based on a *feedback* layout where the signal level was measured after the amplifier.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] There are a number of technologies used for variable-gain amplification, each having different advantages and disadvantages.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Vacuum tubes are used in a configuration called *variable-mu* where the grid-to-cathode voltage changes to alter the gain.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Optical compressors use a photoresistor stimulated by a small lamp (incandescent, LED, or electroluminescent panel) to create changes in signal gain.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Other technologies used include field effect transistors and a diode bridge.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] When working with digital audio, digital signal processing (DSP) techniques are commonly used to implement compression as audio plug-ins, in mixing consoles, and in digital audio workstations.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Often the algorithms are used to emulate the above analog technologies.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A number of user-adjustable control parameters and features are used to adjust dynamic range compression signal processing algorithms and components.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor reduces the level of an audio signal if its amplitude exceeds a certain *threshold*.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Threshold is commonly set in decibels (dBFS for digital compressors and dBu for hardware compressors), where a lower threshold (e.g. −60 dB) means a larger portion of the signal is treated.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] When the signal level is below the threshold, no processing is performed and the input signal is passed, unmodified, to the output.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Thus a higher threshold of, e.g., −5 dB, results in less processing, less compression.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Threshold timing behavior is subject to attack and release settings (see below).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] When the signal level goes above threshold, compressor operation is delayed by the *attack* setting.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] For an amount of time determined by the *release* after the input signal has fallen below the threshold, the compressor continues to apply dynamic range compression.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The amount of gain reduction is determined by **ratio**: a ratio of 4:1 means that if input level is 4 dB over the threshold, the output signal level is reduced to 1 dB over the threshold.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The gain and output level has been reduced by 3 dB.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Another way of stating this is that any input signal level over the threshold will, in this case, be output at a level which is only 25% (i.e.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] 1 over 4) as much over the threshold as its input level was.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The highest ratio of $\infty$ :1 is often known as *limiting*, and effectively denotes that any signal above the threshold is brought down to the threshold level once the *attack* time has expired.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor may provide a degree of control over how quickly it acts.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The *attack* is the period when the compressor is decreasing gain in response to the increased level at the input to reach the gain determined by the ratio.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The *release* is the period when the compressor is increasing gain in response to reduced level at the input to reach the output gain determined by the ratio, or, to unity, once the input level has fallen below the threshold.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Because the loudness pattern of the source material is modified by the time-varying operation of compressor, it may change the character of the signal in subtle to quite noticeable ways depending on the attack and release settings used.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The length of each period is determined by the rate of change and the required change in gain.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] For more intuitive operation, a compressor's attack and release controls are labeled as a unit of time (often milliseconds).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This is the amount of time it takes for the gain to change a set amount of dB or a set percentage towards the target gain.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] There is no industry standard for the exact meaning of these time parameters.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In many compressors, the attack and release times are adjustable by the user.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Some compressors, however, have the attack and release times determined by the circuit design and cannot be adjusted.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Sometimes the attack and release times are *automatic* or *program dependent*, meaning that the behavior may change depending on the input signal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Another control a compressor might offer is knee selection.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This controls whether the bend in the response curve between below threshold and above threshold is abrupt (hard) or gradual (soft).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A soft knee slowly increases the compression ratio as the level increases and eventually reaches the compression ratio set by the user.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A soft knee reduces the potentially audible transition from uncompressed to compressed, and is especially applicable for higher ratio settings where the changeover at the threshold would be more noticeable.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A peak-sensing compressor responds to the peak level of the input signal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] While providing tighter peak level control, peak level sensing does not necessarily relate to human perception of loudness.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Some compressors apply a power measurement function (commonly root mean square or RMS) on the input signal before comparing its level to the threshold.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This produces a more relaxed compression that more closely relates to human perception of loudness.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor in *stereo linking* mode applies the same amount of gain reduction to both the left and right channels.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This is done to prevent image shifting that can occur if each channel is compressed individually.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Because a downward compressor only reduces the level of the signal, the ability to add a fixed amount of *make-up gain* at the output is usually provided so that an optimum output level is produced.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The look-ahead function is designed to overcome the problem of being forced to compromise between slow attack rates that produce smooth-sounding gain changes, and fast attack rates capable of catching transients.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Look-ahead is implemented by splitting the input signal and delaying one side (the audio signal) by the look-ahead time.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The non-delayed side (the gain control signal) is used to drive the compression of the delayed signal, which then appears at the output.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This way a smooth-sounding slower attack rate can be used to catch transients.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The cost of this solution is added audio latency through the processor.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is often applied in audio systems for restaurants, retail, and similar public environments that play background music at a relatively low volume and need it compressed, not just to keep the volume fairly constant, but also to make quiet parts of the music audible over ambient noise.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compression can increase average output gain of a power amplifier by 50 to 100% with a reduced dynamic range.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] For paging and evacuation systems, this adds clarity under noisy circumstances and saves on the number of amplifiers required.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is often used in music production to make instruments more consistent in dynamic range, so that they "sit" more nicely in the mix with the other instruments (neither disappear during short periods of time, nor overpower the other instruments during short periods).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Vocal performances in rock music or pop music are compressed for the same reason.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compression can also be used on instrument sounds to create effects not primarily focused on stabilizing the volume.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] For instance, drum and cymbal sounds tend to decay quickly, but a compressor can make the sound appear to have a more sustained tail.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Guitar sounds are often compressed to produce a fuller, more sustained sound.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Adjusting the attack and release time of a compressor can be used increase contrast between the transient and sustain parts of a sounds envelope.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Most devices capable of compressing audio dynamics can also be used to reduce the volume of one audio source when another audio source reaches a certain level; this is called side-chaining.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In electronic dance music, side-chaining is often used on basslines, controlled by the kick drum or a similar percussive trigger, to prevent the two from conflicting, and provide a pulsating, rhythmic dynamic to the sound.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor can be used to reduce sibilance ('ess' sounds) in vocals (de-essing) by feeding the compressor's side-chain an equalized version of the input signal, so that specific, sibilance-related frequencies (typically 4000 to 8000 hz) activate the compressor more.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is used in voice communications in amateur radio that employ single-sideband (SSB) modulation to make a particular station's signal more readable to a distant station, or to make one's station's transmitted signal stand out against others.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] An SSB signal's strength depends on the level of modulation.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor increases the average level of the modulation signal thus increasing the transmitted signal strength.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Most modern amateur radio SSB transceivers have speech compressors built-in.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is also used in land mobile radio, especially in transmitted audio of professional walkie-talkies and remote control dispatch consoles.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is used extensively in broadcasting to boost the perceived volume of sound while reducing the dynamic range of source audio.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] To avoid overmodulation, broadcasters in most countries have legal limits on instantaneous peak volume they may broadcast.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Normally these limits are met by permanently inserted compression hardware in the on-air chain.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Broadcasters use compressors in order that their station sounds louder than comparable stations.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The effect is to make the more heavily compressed station jump out at the listener at a given volume setting.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This is not limited to inter-channel differences; they also exist between programme material within the same channel.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Loudness differences are a frequent source of audience complaints, especially TV commercials and promos that seem too loud.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) has been addressing this issue in the EBU PLOUD group, which consists of over 240 audio professionals, many from broadcasters and equipment manufacturers.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In 2010, the EBU published EBU R 128 which introduces a new way of metering and normalizing audio.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The Recommendation uses ITU-R BS.1770 loudness metering.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] As of 2016, several European TV stations have announced their support for the new norm and over 20 manufacturers have announced products supporting the new *EBU Mode* loudness meters.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] To help audio engineers understand what loudness range their material consists of (e.g. to check if some compression may be needed to fit it into the channel of a specific delivery platform), the EBU also introduced the *Loudness Range* (LRA) descriptor.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Most television commercials are heavily compressed to achieve near-maximum perceived loudness while staying within permissible limits.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This causes a problem that TV viewers often notice: when a station switches from minimally compressed program material to a heavily compressed commercial, the volume sometimes seems to increase dramatically.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Peak loudness might be the same—meeting the letter of the law—but high compression puts much more of the audio in the commercial at close to the maximum allowable, making the commercial seem much louder.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Record companies, mixing engineers and mastering engineers have been gradually increasing the overall loudness of commercial albums.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This is achieved by using higher degrees of compression and limiting during mixing and mastering; compression algorithms have been engineered specifically to accomplish the task of maximizing audio level in the digital stream.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Hard limiting or clipping can result, affecting the tone and timbre of the music.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The effort to increase loudness has been referred to as the loudness war.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Noise reduction systems use a compressor to reduce the dynamic range of a signal for transmission or recording, expanding it afterward, a process called companding.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This reduces the effects of a channel or recording medium with limited dynamic range.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Instrument amplifiers often include compression circuitry to prevent sudden high-wattage peaks that could damage the speakers.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Electric bass players often use compression effects, either effects units available in pedal, rackmount units, or built-in devices in bass amps, to even out the sound levels of their basslines.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Gain pumping, where a regular amplitude peak (such as a kick drum) causes the rest of the mix to change in volume due to the compressor, is generally avoided in music production.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] However, many dance and hip-hop musicians purposefully use this phenomenon, causing the mix to alter in volume rhythmically in time with the beat.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Hearing aids use a compressor to bring the audio volume into the listener's hearing range.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] To help the patient perceive the direction sound comes from, some hearing aids use binaural compression.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compressors are also used for hearing protection in some electronic active hearing protection earmuffs and earplugs, to let sounds at ordinary volumes be heard normally while attenuating louder sounds, possibly also amplifying softer sounds.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This allows, for example, shooters wearing hearing protection at a shooting range to converse normally, while sharply attenuating the much louder sounds of the gunshots, and similarly for musicians to hear quiet music but be protected from loud noises such as drums or cymbal crashes.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In applications of machine learning where an algorithm is training on audio samples, dynamic range compression is a way to augment samples for a larger data set.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A limiter is a compressor with a high ratio and, generally, a fast attack time.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Compression with ratio of 10:1 or more is generally considered limiting.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Some bass amps and PA system amplifiers include limiters to prevent sudden volume peaks from causing distortion or damaging the speakers.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor with a side-chain input controls gain from main input to output based on the level of the signal at the side-chain input.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] An early innovator of side-chain compression in an effects unit was the Eventide Omnipressor from 1974.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] With side-chaining, the compressor behaves in the conventional manner when both main and side-chain inputs are supplied with the same signal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The side-chain input is used by disc jockeys for ducking – lowering the music volume automatically when speaking.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The DJ's microphone signal is routed to the side-chain input so that whenever the DJ speaks the compressor reduces the volume of the music.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] A sidechain with equalization controls can be used to reduce the volume of signals that have a strong spectral content within a certain frequency range: it can act as a de-esser, reducing the level of vocal sibilance in the range of 6–9 kHz.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Another use of the side-chain in music production serves to maintain a loud bass track without the bass drum causing undue peaks that result in loss of overall headroom.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Inserting the compressor in a parallel signal path is known as parallel compression.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] It is a form of upward compression that facilitates dynamic control without significant audible side effects so long as the ratio is relatively low and the compressor's sound is relatively neutral.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] On the other hand, a high compression ratio with significant audible artifacts can be chosen in one of the two parallel signal paths.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This is used by some concert mixers and recording engineers as an artistic effect called *New York compression* or *Motown compression*.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Combining a linear signal with a compressor and then reducing the output gain of the compression chain results in low-level detail enhancement without any peak reduction; The compressor significantly adds to the combined gain at low levels only.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Multiband compressors can act differently on different frequency bands.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The advantage of multiband compression over full-bandwidth compression is that problems related to a specific frequency range can be fixed without unnecessary compression in the other, unrelated frequencies.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The downside is that frequency-specific compression is more complex and requires more processing capacity than full-bandwidth compression and can introduce phase issues.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Multiband compressors work by first splitting the signal through some number of band-pass filters, crossover filters or filter banks.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Each split signal then passes through its own compressor and is independently adjustable for threshold, ratio, attack, and release.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The signals are then recombined and an additional limiting circuit may be employed to ensure that the combined signals do not create unwanted peak levels.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In music production, multiband compressors are primarily an audio mastering tool, but their inclusion in digital audio workstation plug-in sets is increasing their use among mix engineers.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The TC Electronic Finalizer included a three band compressor and was a popular audio mastering tool around year 2000.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] On-air signal chains of radio stations commonly use multiband compressors to increase loudness while avoiding overmodulation.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Having a louder sound is often considered an advantage in commercial broadcasting.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In recent years, aggressive multiband compression (known as OTT, after a preset for Ableton Lives stock multiband compressor) , has become associated with a certain sonic character often pursued loud electronic music genres like Dubstep.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Serial compression is a technique used in sound recording and mixing.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Serial compression is achieved by using two fairly different compressors in a signal chain.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] One compressor generally stabilizes the dynamic range while the other aggressively compresses stronger peaks.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This is the normal internal signal routing in common combination devices marketed as *compressor-limiters*, where an RMS compressor (for general gain control) is followed by a fast peak-sensing limiter (for overload protection).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Done properly, even heavy serial compression can sound natural in a way not possible with a single compressor.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] It is most often used to even out erratic vocals and guitars.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Some software audio players support plugins that implement compression.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] These can increase loudness of audio tracks, or level out the volume of highly-variable music (such as classical music, or a playlist that spans multiple music types).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] This improves the listenability of audio played through poor-quality speakers, or when played in noisy environments (such as in a car or during a party).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In an article published in January 2014 by the *Journal of the Audio Engineering Society*, Emmanuel Deruty and Damien Tardieu performed a systematic study describing the influence of compressors and brickwall limiters on the musical audio signal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The experiment involved four software limiters: Waves L2, Sonnox Oxford Limiter, Thomas Mundt's Loudmax, Blue Cat's Protector, as well as four software compressors: Waves H-Comp, Sonnox Oxford Dynamics, Sonalksis SV-3157, and URS 1970.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The study provides objective data on what limiters and compressors do to the audio signal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Five signal descriptors were considered: RMS power, EBU R 128 integrated loudness, crest factor, R 128 LRA, and density of clipped samples.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] RMS power accounts for the signal's physical level, R 128 loudness for the perceived level.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] The crest factor, which is the difference between the signal's peak and its average power, is on occasions considered as a basis for the measure of micro-dynamics, for instance in the *TT Dynamic Range Meter* plug-in.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Finally, R 128 LRA has been repeatedly considered as a measure of macro-dynamics or dynamics in the musical sense.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In other words, limiters increase both physical and perceptual levels, increase the density of clipped samples, decrease the crest factor and decrease macro-dynamics (LRA) given that the amount of limiting is substantial.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] As far as the compressors are concerned, the authors performed two processing sessions, using a fast attack (0.5 ms) in one case, and a slow attack (50 ms) in the other.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] Make-up gain is deactivated, but the resulting file is normalized.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In other words, fast-attack compressors increase both physical and perceptual levels, but only slightly.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] They decrease the density of clipped samples, and decrease both crest factor and macro-dynamics.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/dynamic-range-compression] In other words, slow-attack compressors decrease both physical and perceptual levels, decrease macro-dynamics, but have no influence on crest factor and clipped sample density.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] In electronics, **gain** is a measure of the ability of a two-port circuit (often an amplifier) to increase the power or amplitude of a signal from the input to the output port by adding energy converted from some power supply to the signal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] It is usually defined as the mean ratio of the signal amplitude or power at the output port to the amplitude or power at the input port.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] It is often expressed using the logarithmic decibel (dB) units ("dB gain").
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] A gain greater than one (greater than zero dB), that is, amplification, is the defining property of an active device or circuit, while a passive circuit will have a gain of less than one.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] The term *gain* alone is ambiguous, and can refer to the ratio of output to input voltage (*voltage gain*), current (*current gain*) or electric power (*power gain*).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] In the field of audio and general purpose amplifiers, especially operational amplifiers, the term usually refers to voltage gain, but in radio frequency amplifiers it usually refers to power gain.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] Furthermore, the term gain is also applied in systems such as sensors where the input and output have different units; in such cases the gain units must be specified, as in "5 microvolts per photon" for the responsivity of a photosensor.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] The "gain" of a bipolar transistor normally refers to forward current transfer ratio, either *h*FE ("beta", the static ratio of *I**c* divided by *I*b at some operating point), or sometimes *h*fe (the small-signal current gain, the slope of the graph of *I**c* against *I**b* at a point).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] The gain of an electronic device or circuit generally varies with the frequency of the applied signal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] Unless otherwise stated, the term refers to the gain for frequencies in the passband, the intended operating frequency range of the equipment.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] The term *gain* has a different meaning in antenna design; antenna gain is the ratio of radiation intensity from a directional antenna to $P_{\text{in}}/4\pi$ (mean radiation intensity from a lossless antenna).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] where $P_{\text{in}}$ is the power applied to the input, $P_{\text{out}}$ is the power from the output.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] This simplified formula, the 20 log rule, is used to calculate a **voltage gain** in decibels and is equivalent to a power gain if and only if the impedances at input and output are equal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] This simplified formula is used to calculate a **current gain** in decibels and is equivalent to the power gain if and only if the impedances at input and output are equal.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] The "current gain" of a bipolar transistor, $h_{\text{FE}}$ or $h_{\text{fe}}$ , is normally given as a dimensionless number, the ratio of $I_{\text{c}}$ to $I_{\text{b}}$ (or slope of the $I_{\text{c}}$ -versus- $I_{\text{b}}$ graph, for $h_{\text{fe}}$ ).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] In the cases above, gain will be a dimensionless quantity, as it is the ratio of like units (decibels are not used as units, but rather as a method of indicating a logarithmic relationship).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] In the bipolar transistor example, it is the ratio of the output current to the input current, both measured in amperes.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] In the case of other devices, the gain will have a value in SI units.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] Such is the case with the operational transconductance amplifier, which has an open-loop gain (transconductance) in siemens (mhos), because the gain is a ratio of the output current to the input voltage.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] An amplifier has an input impedance of 50 ohms and drives a load of 50 ohms.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] When its input ( $V_{\text{in}}$ ) is 1 volt, its output ( $V_{\text{out}}$ ) is 10 volts.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] The units V/V are optional but make it clear that this figure is a voltage gain and not a power gain.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/gain-electronics] A gain of factor 1 (equivalent to 0 dB) where both input and output are at the same voltage level and impedance is also known as *unity gain*.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] In acoustics, **loudness** is the subjective perception of sound pressure.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] More formally, it is defined as the "attribute of auditory sensation in terms of which sounds can be ordered on a scale extending from quiet to loud".
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] The relation of physical attributes of sound to perceived loudness includes physical, physiological and psychological components.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] The study of **apparent loudness** is included in the topic of psychoacoustics and employs methods of psychophysics.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] In different industries, loudness may have different meanings and different measurement standards.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Some definitions, such as ITU-R BS.1770 refer to the relative loudness of different segments of electronically reproduced sounds, such as for broadcasting and cinema.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Others, such as ISO 532A (Stevens loudness, measured in sones), ISO 532B (Zwicker loudness), DIN 45631 and ASA/ANSI S3.4, have a more general scope and are often used to characterize the loudness of environmental noise.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] More modern standards, such as Nordtest ACOU112 and ISO/AWI 532-3 (in progress), take into account other components of loudness, such as onset rate, time variation and spectral masking.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Loudness, a subjective measure, is often confused with physical measures of sound strength such as sound pressure, sound pressure level (in decibels), sound intensity or sound power.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Weighting filters such as A-weighting and LKFS attempt to compensate measurements to correspond to loudness as perceived by the typical human.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] The perception of loudness is related to sound pressure level (SPL), frequency content and duration of a sound.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] The relationship between SPL and loudness of a single tone can be approximated by Stevens's power law in which SPL has an exponent of 0.67.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] A more precise model known as the *Inflected Exponential function*, indicates that loudness increases with a higher exponent at low and high levels and with a lower exponent at moderate levels.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] The sensitivity of the human ear changes as a function of frequency, as shown in the equal-loudness graph.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Each line on this graph shows the SPL required for frequencies to be perceived as equally loud, and different curves pertain to different sound pressure levels.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] It also shows that humans with normal hearing are most sensitive to sounds around 2–4 kHz, with sensitivity declining to either side of this region.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] A complete model of the perception of loudness will include the integration of SPL by frequency.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Historically, loudness was measured using an ear-balancing method with an audiometer in which the amplitude of a sine wave was adjusted by the user to equal the perceived loudness of the sound being evaluated.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Contemporary standards for measurement of loudness are based on the summation of energy in critical bands.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] When sensorineural hearing loss (damage to the cochlea or in the brain) is present, the perception of loudness is altered.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Sounds at low levels (often perceived by those without hearing loss as relatively quiet) are no longer audible to the hearing impaired, but sounds at high levels often are perceived as having the same loudness as they would for an unimpaired listener.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] This phenomenon can be explained by two theories, called *loudness recruitment* and *softness imperception*.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Loudness recruitment posits that loudness grows more rapidly for certain listeners than for normal listeners with changes in level.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] This theory has been accepted as the classical explanation.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Softness imperception, a term coined by Mary Florentine around 2002, proposes that some listeners with sensorineural hearing loss may exhibit a normal rate of loudness growth, but instead have an elevated loudness at their threshold.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] That is, the softest sound that is audible to these listeners is louder than the softest sound audible to normal listeners.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] The *loudness* control associated with a loudness compensation feature on some consumer stereos alters the frequency response curve to correspond roughly with the equal loudness characteristic of the ear.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Loudness compensation is intended to make the recorded music sound more natural when played at a lower levels by boosting low frequencies, to which the ear is less sensitive at lower sound pressure levels.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Loudness normalization is a specific type of audio normalization that equalizes perceived level such that, for instance, commercials do not sound louder than television programs.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Loudness normalization schemes exist for a number of audio applications.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Historically sone (loudness *N*) and phon (loudness level *LN*) units have been used to measure loudness.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] A-weighting follows human sensitivity to sound and describes relative perceived loudness for at quiet to moderate speech levels, around 40 phons.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Relative loudness monitoring in production is measured in accordance with ITU-R BS.1770 in units of LKFS.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Work began on ITU-R BS.1770 in 2001 after 0 dBFS+ level distortion in converters and lossy codecs had become evident; and the original Leq(RLB) loudness metric was proposed by Gilbert Soulodre in 2003.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Based on data from subjective listening tests, Leq(RLB) compared favorably to numerous other algorithms.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] CBC, Dolby and TC Electronic and numerous broadcasters contributed to the listening tests.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] Loudness levels measured according to the Leq(RLB) specified in ITU-R BS.1770 are reported in LKFS units.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] The ITU-R BS.1770 measurement system was improved for multi-channel applications (monaural to 5.1 surround sound).
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] To improve consistency across program material genres, a relative measurement gate was added.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] This work was carried out in 2008 by the EBU.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] The improvements were brought back into BS.1770-2.
[src:dynamic-range-compression/loudness] ITU subsequently updated the true-peak metric (BS.1770-3) and added provision for even more audio channels, for instance 22.2 surround sound (BS.1770-4).
